The '''100 Year Starship''' ('''100YSS''') is a joint U.S. [[Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA) and [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA) grant project to a private entity. The goal of the study is not to have the government fund the actual building of spacecraft, but rather to create a business plan that can last 100 years in order to help foster the research needed for [[interstellar travel]].<ref name="NYT-Aug-2011">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/18/science/space/18starship.html?pagewanted=all |title=Offering Funds, U.S. Agency Dreams of Sending Humans to Stars |first=Dennis |last=Overbye |date=August 18, 2011 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=Chang2011>{{Cite news |first=Kenneth |last=Chang |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/science/space/18starship.html |title=Not Such a Stretch to Reach for the Stars |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 17, 2011 |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="Belfiore 2011">{{Cite web |first=Michael |last=Belfiore |url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/space/deep/to-infinity-and-beyond-at-darpas-100-year-starship-symposium |title=To Infinity and Beyond at DARPA’s 100-Year Starship Symposium |work=[[Popular Mechanics]] |date=September 30, 2011 |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>
==Origin== The 100 Year Starship effort was announced by NASA [[Ames Research Center]] director [[Pete Worden]] in a talk at San Francisco's Long Conversation conference in October 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brandon|first1=John|title=Is NASA Covering Up the 100-Year Starship?|url=http://www.foxnews.com/scitech/2010/10/29/nasa-cover-up-hundred-year-starship/|accessdate=18 June 2014|publisher=[[FoxNews.com]]|date=October 29, 2010}}</ref> In a DARPA press release officially announcing the effort,<ref>{{cite web|title=DARPA/NASA Seek to Inspire Multigenerational Research and Development|url=http://www.darpa.mil/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=1799|publisher=Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency|accessdate=18 June 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810105006/http://www.darpa.mil/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=1799|archivedate=10 August 2014|df=}}</ref> program manager [[Paul Eremenko]], who served as the study coordinator, explained that the endeavor was meant to excite several generations to commit to the research and development of breakthrough technologies to advance the eventual goal of interstellar space travel.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Page|first1=Lewis|title=DARPA, NASA team on '100-Year Starship' project: plan to invent Heinlein style miracle nonprofit first|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/11/03/100_year_starship/|accessdate=18 June 2014|publisher=[[The Register]]|date=November 3, 2010}}</ref>
==Foundation== The 100 Year Starship study was the name of a one-year project to assess the attributes of and lay the groundwork for an organization that can carry forward the 100 Year Starship vision.<ref name= "2012symposium">{{cite web|title= 100 Year Starship Study™ 2012 Public Symposium |url=http://www.100yss.org/pdf/100YSSAgenda_0902.pdf | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227203817/http://www.100yss.org/pdf/100YSSAgenda_0902.pdf | archivedate=February 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref name= "january">{{cite web|title= The 100-Year Starship Study |url=http://www.100yss.org/pdf/100YSS_January_Synopsis.pdf | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203110443/http://www.100yss.org/pdf/100YSS_January_Synopsis.pdf | archivedate=December 3, 2011}}</ref>
The winning bid to spearhead the 100 Year Starship effort was the Dorothy Jemison Foundation for Excellence, partnering with [[Icarus Interstellar]] and the [[Foundation for Enterprise Development]], led by the American physician and former NASA astronaut [[Mae Jemison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2199247/The-100-year-Starship-project-plans-transport-humans-solar-system.html|title=The 100-year Starship project that plans to transport humans beyond the solar system|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|language=English|author=Mark Prigg|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="BBC 2011">{{cite web |title=Former astronaut to lead starship effort| first=Sharon |last=Weinberger| date=5 January 2012| work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=21 May 2014| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-16427876}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=21212 |first=Paul |last=Gilster |title=100 Year Starship Winner Announced |date=6 January 2012 |work=Centauri Dreams |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> In 2013, the consortium was awarded a $500,000 grant for further work. The new organization maintains the organizational name 100 Year Starship.<ref name=atlantic201202>{{cite journal |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/02/project-icarus-laying-the-plans-for-interstellar-travel/253335/ |title=Project Icarus: Laying the Plans for Interstellar Travel |first=Ross |last=Andersen |journal=[[The Atlantic]] |date=February 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>
Neither Icarus Interstellar nor the Foundation for Enterprise Development are any longer involved{{since when|date=November 2018}} in 100 Year Starship although initial grant negotiations took place.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
==100 Year Starship Symposia== Before the solicitation for the foundation, the 100 Year Starship project was preceded by a conference held in [[Orlando, Florida]], from September 30 to October 2, 2011, co-sponsored by DARPA and NASA, organized by DARPA's Tactical Technology Office director, David Neyland.<ref name=Chang2011/><ref name="Belfiore 2011"/> The conference included presentations on the technology, biology, physics, philosophy, sociology, and economics of interstellar flight.<ref name= "2012symposium"/> Selected papers from the conference were published in the [[Journal of the British Interplanetary Society]].{{clarify|date=November 2018}}<!-- a source link to the journal issue that had these would be appropriate here -->
After the Jemison Foundation was named as winner of the grant, a second symposium was held in 2012 in [[Houston]]. Papers on a number of subjects related to interstellar flight and organization of the foundation were presented.<ref name= "2012symposium" /> 2013 and 2014 Symposia were held in Houston,<ref name=100yss2014>{{cite web |url=http://100yss.org/symposium/2014 |title=100 Year Simposium 2014 |date=2013 |accessdate=2014-05-25 }}</ref> and a fifth on September 2015.{{cn|date=November 2018}}{{update after|2018|11|26}}
== Canopus Awards == In 2015, the 100 Year Starship project hosted its first annual Canopus Awards for excellence in interstellar writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://100yss.org/news/press |title=100 Year Starship Celebrates Halloween Eve Awarding First Interstellar Writing Prize During Science Fiction Stories Night |date=20 October 2015 |work=100yss.org |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> The winners were announced October 30, 2015 at the symposium:<ref>{{Cite web| title = Locus Online News » Canopus Award Winners| url = http://www.locusmag.com/News/2015/11/canopus-award-winners/| website = www.locusmag.com| accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref> * Previously Published Long-Form Fiction (40,000 words or more): ''InterstellarNet: Enigma'' by [[Edward M. Lerner]] (FoxAcre). {{ISBN|978-1936771646}} * Previously Published Short-Form Fiction (between 1,000 and 40,000 words): “The Waves” by [[Ken Liu]] ([[Asimov's Science Fiction|Asimov's]] 12/12) * Original Fiction (1,000-5,000 words): [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304221645/https://klews39.wordpress.com/2015/03/03/everetts-awakening/ “Everett's Awakening”] by Yelcho * Original Non-Fiction (1,000-5,000 words): “Finding Earth 2.0 from the Focus of the Solar Gravitational Lens” by [[Louis Friedman]] & [[Slava Turyshev]]
==Criticism== The 100 Year Starship was named in 2012 by U.S. [[Senator Tom Coburn]] as one of the 100 most wasteful government spending projects. Coburn specifically cited a 100 Year Starship workshop that included one session, entitled “Did Jesus die for [[Klingons]] too?” that debated the implications for Christian philosophy should life be found on other planets.<ref>http://www.washingtontimes.com/blog/inside-politics/2012/nov/15/pentagon-wants-know-did-jesus-die-klingons-too/</ref><ref>https://www.cnbc.com/id/49844670</ref> The original meetings were hard science; not so for the ones that followed under Jemison's leadership.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
