[[File:HermanHaga.jpg|thumb|Herman Haga]] '''Herman Haga''' ([[Oldeboorn]], 24 January 1852 – [[Zeist]], 11 September 1936) was a Dutch physicist.
==Career== Haga studied physics from 1871 to 1876 at the [[University of Leiden]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Klaas van Berkel| authorlink = Klaas van Berkel| title=''De onbekende Herman Haga, medeoprichter van de NNV'' (The unknown Herman Haga, founder of the NNV (Nederlandse Natuurkundige Vereniging) Dutch Physics Association)|journal=Nederlands Tijdschrift voor Natuurkunde|date=August 2011|volume=77|issue=8|pages=296–298}}</ref> He received his PhD with thesis ''Over de absorptie van stralende warmte door waterdamp'' (On the absorption of radiant heat by water vapor)<ref>{{cite web|author=Herman Haga |url=http://ilorentz.org/history/proefschriften/sources/Haga_1876.pdf |title=Over de absorptie van stralende warmte door waterdamp |year=1876}}</ref> under the direction of [[Pieter Rijke|Pieter L. Rijke]]. From 1886 to 1921 Haga was professor of physics at the [[University of Groningen]], where he designed and oversaw the building of a new physics laboratory, opened in 1892. From 1900 Haga was also the rector of the University of Gronigen. He performed experiments on the voltage of the [[Weston cell]]; these experiments lead to the modern definition of the [[volt]]. With Cornelis Wind, Haga passed X-rays through a 15-micrometer slit as a source with a V-shaped narrowing slit as a target. The target slit was 27 micrometers at the opening and nearly 0 micrometers at the output. Haga and Wind interpreted a diffuse broadening of the X-rays emitted at the narrower end of the slit as a diffraction pattern.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Haga, Herman|author2=Wind, Cornelis|title=De buiging der Röntgenstralen|journal=Versl. Kon. Ak. Wet.|year=1899|volume=7|pages=500–507}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Haga, Herman|author2=Wind, Cornelis|title=Die Beugung von Röntgenstrahlen|journal=Annalen der Physik|year=1899|volume=68|pages=884–895|doi=10.1002/andp.18993040820 |bibcode = 1899AnP...304..884H }} (Haga and Wind's German version of ''De buiging der Röntgenstralen'')</ref>
Haga was one of the founders of the ''Nederlandse Natuurkundige Vereniging'' (Dutch Physics Association). In addition to Cornelis Harm Wind (1867–1911),<ref>Cornelis Wind held the chair of theoretical physics at the [[University of Utrecht]], and, when he died at the age of 43, he was succeeded by [[Peter Debye]].</ref> Haga's doctoral students include the crystallographer Pieter Terpstra (1886–1973)<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n86-861526 Terpstra, P. b. 1886 (Pieter) WorldCat Identities]</ref> and Ekko Oosterhuis (1886–1966), who was the second scientist to join the ''[[Philips Natuurkundig Laboratorium]]''.<ref>[http://www.dos4ever.com/EF50/Oosterhuis.html Dr. Ekko Oosterhuis]</ref>
In 1896 Haga became a member of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dwc.knaw.nl/biografie/pmknaw/?pagetype=authorDetail&aId=PE00000619 |title=Herman Haga (1852 - 1936) |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |accessdate=24 January 2016}}</ref>
