{{Infobox settlement | name = King City weather radar station | image_skyline = | image_alt = A tapering steel tower on a grassy hill supports a white sphere. The six-storey tower is in front of a small one-storey building surrounded by rolling hills and forest. The background is a bright blue sky with numerous clouds | image_caption = Tower and [[radome]] of the old radar prior to the upgrade to the dual-polarization radar | image_flag = | flag_alt = | image_seal = | seal_alt = | image_shield = | shield_alt = | nickname = | motto = | image_map = | map_alt = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_map_alt = | pushpin_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|43|57|50|N|79|34|25|W|region:CA|display=inline,title}} | coor_pinpoint = | coordinates_footnotes = | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = Canada | subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Ontario]] | subdivision_type2 = [[Regional municipality]] | subdivision_name2 = [[York Region]] | subdivision_type3 = Township | subdivision_name3 = [[King, Ontario|King]] | subdivision_type4 = Community | subdivision_name4 = [[King City, Ontario|King City]] | established_title = <!-- Established --> | established_date = | leader_title = | leader_name = | unit_pref = Metric | dimensions_footnotes = | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 360 | timezone1 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] | utc_offset1 = −05:00 | timezone1_DST = Eastern Daylight Time | utc_offset1_DST = −04:00 | website = | footnotes = | blank_name_sec1 = Type | blank_info_sec1 = [[Research station]] and [[weather radar]] }}
The '''King City weather radar station''' ([[ICAO]] site identifier '''CWKR''') is a [[weather radar]] located in [[King City, Ontario|King City]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. It is operated by [[Environment Canada]] and is part of the [[Canadian weather radar network]], for which it is the primary [[research station]].
The 16.45 hectare{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}} site is listed at an elevation of 360&nbsp;m, and the tower is 27&nbsp;m tall.{{sfn|Environment Canada|2002}}
Mounted on the tower is a 5&nbsp;cm weather radar, and a [[C band (IEEE)|C-band]] dual-polarization radar system was installed at the site in 2004.{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}}
==Research== The station serves a number of research roles, and collects data to fulfill those observational needs. It is "responsible for providing national leadership on radar meteorology research applications".{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}}
In 1984, the Research Directorate of the [[Atmospheric Environment Service]] established the first Canadian [[weather radar]] with [[Weather radar#Velocity|Doppler capability]] in King City.{{sfn|Crozier|Joe|Scott|Herscovitch|1991}} In 2004, a dual-polarization radar was installed for further research.{{sfn|Sills|2004}} These systems are used for predictive purposes, and the data collected is used for weather forecasts for the [[Greater Toronto Area]] and the [[Golden Horseshoe (Ontario)|Golden Horseshoe]].
Further, under the auspices of the Cloud Physics and Severe Weather Research Section of Environment Canada, the King Doppler Weather Radar Research Facility collects data for research.
The C-band radar can be useful for observing [[bird migration]] patterns, especially when data is taken in aggregate with that of other radar stations. Current active research in dual-polarization radar includes winter precipitation, detection and short-term forecasting of high-impact weather events,{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}} quantitative precipitation estimation,{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}} satellite validation,{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}} and particle type identification.
==Equipment== The WSR82D radar installed in 1982 had a fiberglass laminate radome, and a parabolic reflector with a diameter of 6.1m and linear horizontal polarisation.{{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}} Its [[Gain (electronics)|gain]] was 48 dB.{{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}} The radar emitted a 260kW beam with a [[frequency]] of 5625 MHz and [[wavelength]] of 5.33cm having a [[beam width]] of 0.65 degrees.{{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}} In conventional operation, it had a [[pulse duration]] of 2µs, [[pulse repetition frequency]] of 250 pulses per second, and performed 6.0 scanning rotations per minute.{{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}} In [[Weather radar#Velocity|Doppler]] operation, it had a pulse duration of 0.5µs, pulse repetition frequency of 892 or 1190 pulses per second, and a scan rate of 0.75 rotations per minute. {{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}} In long-range Doppler operation, a pulse repetition frequency of 650 pulses per second and a scan rate of 2 rotations per minute were used.{{sfn|Raghavan|2003|p=45}}
It was replaced in 2004 by a similar radar but with [[dual polarization]] capabilities.{{sfn|Environment Canada|2008}}
