The following is a '''list of centroids''' of various [[two-dimensional]] objects. The [[centroid]] of an object <math>X</math> in <math>n</math>-[[dimension]]al [[space (mathematics)|space]] is the intersection of all [[hyperplane]]s that divide <math>X</math> into two parts of equal [[moment (physics)|moment]] about the hyperplane. Informally, it is the "[[average]]" of all points of <math>X</math>. For an object of uniform composition (mass, density, etc.) the centroid of a body is also its [[Center of mass|center of mass]]. In the case of two-dimensional objects shown below, the hyperplanes are simply lines.
