'''Pamela Dalton''' is a [[cognitive psychologist]]. She has a Ph.D. in experimental psychology and a Masters in Public Health. Dalton is frequently quoted by the popular press as an authority on environmental odors.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9900E4DC1F3AF932A35757C0A9679C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | title=THE HOME FRONT; A Nose With An Eye | first=Julia | last=Szabo | date=2001-04-01 | accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>
She is most notable for her contributions to the research toward the fields of [[sick building syndrome]] and [[multiple chemical sensitivity]].<ref>{{Citation | first = Pamela | last = Dalton | author-link = | first2 = | last2 = | author2-link = | editor-last = | editor-first = | editor2-last = | editor2-first = | contribution = | contribution-url = | title = Odor Perception and Beliefs about Risk | year = 1996 | pages = | place = Monell Chemical Senses Center | publisher = Chemical Senses | url = http://chemse.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/21/4/447 | doi = | id = }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|first=Pamela |last=Dalton |author-link= |first2=Nadine |last2=Doolittle |author2-link= |editor-last= |editor-first= |editor2-last= |editor2-first= |contribution= |contribution-url= |title=Gender-specific induction of enhanced sensitivity to odors |year=2002 |pages= |place=Monell Chemical Senses Center |publisher=Nature Neuroscience |url=http://www.nature.com/neuro/journal/v5/n3/suppinfo/nn803_S1.html;jsessionid=F5063AD04B6D6A06FA54A52FC68437DD |doi= |id= |format= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525112514/http://www.nature.com/neuro/journal/v5/n3/suppinfo/nn803_S1.html;jsessionid=F5063AD04B6D6A06FA54A52FC68437DD |archivedate=May 25, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Bouchez | first = Colette | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title = Fragrance Allergies: A Sensory Assault | date = | year = | url = http://www.webmd.com/allergies/features/fragrance-allergies-a-sensory-assault | accessdate = 2008-08-06}}</ref> In the past she has worked with the [[United States Department of Defense]] on ''nonlethal weapons development'', or the enhancement of bad odors as weapons.<ref>{{Citation | last = Kahn | first = Jennifer | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title = Aroma Therapy: In The Military, It's Known As 'Nonlethal Weapons Development' | date = May 22, 2001 | url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/gate/archive/2001/05/22/smell.DTL | accessdate = 2008-08-06 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref><ref>http://www.scienceblog.com/community/older/2001/C/200113657.html</ref><ref name="timesonline">{{Citation | last=Schopen | first=Fay | date=2008-06-11 | title=Pamela Dalton - creator of the world's nastiest smell | publisher=Times Online | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/career_and_jobs/careers_in/careers_in_science/article4111663.ece | accessdate=2008-08-09 | location=London}}</ref> She currently works at the [[Monell Chemical Senses Center]].
She also was a contributor to the [[NIH Toolbox]] for the Assessment of Neurological and Behavioral Function (www.nihtoolbox.org), as a member of the [[NIH Toolbox]] steering committee and the Olfaction team, developing the NIH Toolbox Odor Identification Test.<ref>Dalton P, Mennella JA, Cowart BJ, Maute C, Pribitkin EA, Reilly JS. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3046421/ Evaluating the Prevalence of Olfactory Dysfunction in a Pediatric Population]. Ann. N. Y. Acad. Sci. 2009;1170(1):537-542.</ref><ref>Dalton P, Mennella JA, Maute C, Castor SM, Silva-Garcia A, Slotkin J. Development of a test to evaluate olfactory function in a pediatric population. Laryngoscope. 2011;121(9):1843-1850.</ref> The contract for the [[NIH Toolbox]] for the Assessment of Neurological and Behavioral Function (www.nihtoolbox.org) was initiated by the NIH Blueprint for Neuroscience Research (www.neuroscienceblueprint.nih.gov) in 2006 to develop a set of state-of-the-art measurement tools to enhance collection of data in large cohort studies in biomedical research.<ref>National Institutes of Health.NIH Toolbox is open. A new set of tools to help scientists measure the ways we think, move, feel and sense the world is ready for use in studies.... NIH Record newsletter, October 26th 2012</ref><ref>Talan, Jamie. [http://journals.lww.com/neurotodayonline/Fulltext/2012/11010/NEWS_FROM_THE_NINDS__New_NIH_Toolbox_Rolled_Out.13.aspx New NIH Toolbox Rolled Out for Standardized Behavioral and Clinical Assessment Measures.Neurology Today]. 2012; 12(21):7</ref>
