'''The Tale of Shim Chong''' ({{Korean|hangul=심청전|rr=Simcheongjeon}}) is a [[Korea]]n folk story.<ref name=Bärtås/> ''[[Simcheongga]]'' is the ''[[pansori]]'' (traditional musical storytelling) of the tale.<ref>재미있는 우리국악 이야기, 서해문집</ref> It was adapted on screen by [[Shin Sang-ok]] twice, once in South Korea in 1972,<ref>{{cite book|last=Schönherr|first=Johannes|title=North Korean Cinema: A History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IGBog0seMFQC&pg=PA81|date=2012|location=Jefferson|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-9052-3|page=81}}
</ref> and as ''[[The Tale of Shim Chong (film)|The Tale of Shim Chong]]'' in 1985 when he and his wife [[Choi Eun-hee]] were [[Abduction of Shin Sang-ok and Choi Eun-hee|abducted to North Korea]].<ref name=Bärtås>{{cite book|last1=Bärtås|first1=Magnus|last2=Ekman|first2=Fredrik|title=Hirviöidenkin on kuoltava: Ryhmämatka Pohjois-Koreaan|year=2014|publisher=Tammi|location=Helsinki|language=fi|isbn=978-951-31-7727-0|trans-title=All Monsters Must Die: An Excursion to North Korea|translator-last=Eskelinen|translator-first=Heikki|page=161}}</ref>

